            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\n**Event:** His first car ride from the airport to Daly City. He remembers pressing his face against the cool glass of the family's borrowed station wagon, mesmerized by the Bayshore Freeway at dusk. It wasn't the city skyline that captivated him, but the endless, intersecting ribbons of concrete and the flowing red and white rivers of light.\n**Emotional Impact:** A profound, almost spiritual sense of awe and order within chaos.\n**Significance:** It was the moment a foreign landscape became a beautiful, complex puzzle he yearned to understand, igniting a lifelong passion.\n**When:** Age seven, 1976.\n\n***\n\n2.\n**Event:** Watching the news coverage of the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake in his sparse college apartment. He saw the footage of the collapsed Cypress Viaduct, a structure he had admired and sketched. It felt like watching a god fall from the sky. The horror was quickly replaced by a cold, bright clarity.\n**Emotional Impact:** Shock and a deep sense of betrayal by the fallibility of a system he trusted, which then hardened into intense resolve.\n**Significance:** This transformed his academic fascination into a moral calling to ensure such a failure never happened again.\n**When:** College student, age 20.\n\n***\n\n3.\n**Event:** On a rainy Saturday, his ten-year-old daughter, Layla, spent hours with him building an intricate Lego model of the Golden Gate Bridge on their living room floor. When they finished, she looked up at him, her expression serious, and asked, \"Is it strong, Baba?\"\n**Emotional Impact:** An overwhelming wave of love and pride, seeing his own core values of strength and safety reflected in his child's eyes.\n**Significance:** It cemented the link between his professional duty and his personal role as a protector and father.\n**When:** His daughter was a child, mid-30s.\n\n***\n\n4.\n**Event:** Standing on a pier at the Port of Oakland in the predawn quiet, watching the first massive container ship being unloaded under a new logistics system he had painstakingly designed. He felt the silent hum of a perfectly solved equation as the cranes moved with an efficiency that hadn't existed the day before.\n**Emotional Impact:** Not triumphant joy, but a deep, quiet, and intensely private satisfaction.\n**Significance:** It was the first tangible proof that his methodical work could create real-world harmony and strength, validating his entire career path.\n**When:** Early in his career, early 30s.\n\n***\n\n5.\n**Event:** Last Tuesday, riding a crowded MUNI N-Judah train home. He noticed a young woman with a laptop open to a complex track switching schematic, her brow furrowed in concentration. He didn't speak to her, but simply observed, feeling a powerful sense of continuity.\n**Emotional Impact:** A calm feeling of hope and contentment, like a gardener seeing a strong new sapling.\n**Significance:** It was a quiet affirmation that the work would continue; the city's vital systems were in the hands of a new generation he hoped to mentor.\n**When:** Recently, age 54."
